27/* \summary: IP over Fibre Channel printer */
28
29/* specification: RFC 2625 */
30
31#ifdef HAVE_CONFIG_H
32#include "config.h"
33#endif
34
35#include <netdissect-stdinc.h>
36
37#include <string.h>
38
39#include "netdissect.h"
40#include "addrtoname.h"
41
42#include "ether.h"
43
44struct ipfc_header {
45 u_char ipfc_dhost[8];
46 u_char ipfc_shost[8];
47};
48
49#define IPFC_HDRLEN 16
50
51/* Extract src, dst addresses */
52static inline void
53extract_ipfc_addrs(const struct ipfc_header *ipfcp, char *ipfcsrc,
54 char *ipfcdst)
55{
56 /*
57 * We assume that, as per RFC 2625, the lower 48 bits of the
58 * source and destination addresses are MAC addresses.
59 */
60 memcpy(ipfcdst, (const char *)&ipfcp->ipfc_dhost[2], 6);
61 memcpy(ipfcsrc, (const char *)&ipfcp->ipfc_shost[2], 6);
62}
63
64/*
65 * Print the Network_Header
66 */
67static inline void
68ipfc_hdr_print(netdissect_options *ndo,
69 register const struct ipfc_header *ipfcp _U_,
70 register u_int length, register const u_char *ipfcsrc,
71 register const u_char *ipfcdst)
72{
73 const char *srcname, *dstname;
74
75 srcname = etheraddr_string(ndo, ipfcsrc);
76 dstname = etheraddr_string(ndo, ipfcdst);
77
78 /*
79 * XXX - should we show the upper 16 bits of the addresses?
80 * Do so only if "vflag" is set?
81 * Section 3.3 "FC Port and Node Network Addresses" says that
82 *
83 * In this specification, both the Source and Destination
84 * 4-bit NAA identifiers SHALL be set to binary '0001'
85 * indicating that an IEEE 48-bit MAC address is contained
86 * in the lower 48 bits of the network address fields. The
87 * high order 12 bits in the network address fields SHALL
88 * be set to 0x0000.
89 *
90 * so, for captures following this specification, the upper 16
91 * bits should be 0x1000, followed by a MAC address.
92 */
93 ND_PRINT((ndo, "%s > %s, length %u: ", srcname, dstname, length));
94}
95
96static u_int
97ipfc_print(netdissect_options *ndo, const u_char *p, u_int length, u_int caplen)
98{
99 const struct ipfc_header *ipfcp = (const struct ipfc_header *)p;
100 struct ether_header ehdr;
101 struct lladdr_info src, dst;
102 int llc_hdrlen;
103
104 if (caplen < IPFC_HDRLEN) {
105 ND_PRINT((ndo, "[|ipfc]"));
106 return (caplen);
107 }
108 /*
109 * Get the network addresses into a canonical form
110 */
111 extract_ipfc_addrs(ipfcp, (char *)ESRC(&ehdr), (char *)EDST(&ehdr));
112
113 if (ndo->ndo_eflag)
114 ipfc_hdr_print(ndo, ipfcp, length, ESRC(&ehdr), EDST(&ehdr));
115
116 src.addr = ESRC(&ehdr);
117 src.addr_string = etheraddr_string;
118 dst.addr = EDST(&ehdr);
119 dst.addr_string = etheraddr_string;
120
121 /* Skip over Network_Header */
122 length -= IPFC_HDRLEN;
123 p += IPFC_HDRLEN;
124 caplen -= IPFC_HDRLEN;
125
126 /* Try to print the LLC-layer header & higher layers */
127 llc_hdrlen = llc_print(ndo, p, length, caplen, &src, &dst);
128 if (llc_hdrlen < 0) {
129 /*
130 * Some kinds of LLC packet we cannot
131 * handle intelligently
132 */
133 if (!ndo->ndo_suppress_default_print)
134 ND_DEFAULTPRINT(p, caplen);
135 llc_hdrlen = -llc_hdrlen;
136 }
137 return (IPFC_HDRLEN + llc_hdrlen);
138}
139
140/*
141 * This is the top level routine of the printer. 'p' points
142 * to the Network_Header of the packet, 'h->ts' is the timestamp,
143 * 'h->len' is the length of the packet off the wire, and 'h->caplen'
144 * is the number of bytes actually captured.
145 */
146u_int
147ipfc_if_print(netdissect_options *ndo, const struct pcap_pkthdr *h, register const u_char *p)
148{
149 return (ipfc_print(ndo, p, h->len, h->caplen));
150}
